00:51:15.350 --> 00:51:18.800
AUDIENCE: I'm curious about
your model on the Reddit pizza

00:51:18.800 --> 00:51:20.400
requests.

00:51:20.400 --> 00:51:24.130
Using your probability
model, could you

00:51:24.130 --> 00:51:28.350
come up with the perfect request
and would you get a pizza?

00:51:28.350 --> 00:51:34.660
DAN JURAFSKY: Yes, so Tim
Althoff, the main author

00:51:34.660 --> 00:51:38.130
on that paper, did, in
fact, try getting a pizza

00:51:38.130 --> 00:51:41.440
by using all of the features
that were supposed to work

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:43.250
and he got a pizza.

00:51:43.250 --> 00:51:45.050
So the short answer is yes.

00:51:45.050 --> 00:51:49.249
Of course, some of
these are honest signals

00:51:49.249 --> 00:51:50.540
and some are dishonest signals.

00:51:50.540 --> 00:51:54.370
So an honest signal is something
that you can't really fake

00:51:54.370 --> 00:51:56.110
or that are more
difficult to fake.

00:51:56.110 --> 00:51:59.360
So if you really do need the
pizza because your true story

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:02.062
is that you're absolutely
broke and you can't get out

00:52:02.062 --> 00:52:03.520
of your house and
all these things,

00:52:03.520 --> 00:52:04.400
you're more likely
to get the pizza.

00:52:04.400 --> 00:52:06.270
So some of these things
make a lot of sense.

00:52:06.270 --> 00:52:08.441
Others are more
linguistic dressing.

00:52:08.441 --> 00:52:10.190
AUDIENCE: I'm fascinated
by the way you've

00:52:10.190 --> 00:52:12.270
traced the history
of particular foods

00:52:12.270 --> 00:52:14.090
and I'm just curious if you
could tell us a little bit more

00:52:14.090 --> 00:52:15.280
about your research methods.

00:52:15.280 --> 00:52:16.821
Where do you find
from those sources?

00:52:16.821 --> 00:52:18.650
DAN JURAFSKY: Yeah,
so the ketchup--

00:52:18.650 --> 00:52:21.780
it's absurdly simple now.

00:52:21.780 --> 00:52:24.350
It was much harder when I
started 20 or 30 years ago.

00:52:24.350 --> 00:52:27.400
So, the ketchup story is in
the Oxford English Dictionary

00:52:27.400 --> 00:52:31.450
and it was written
by James Murray,

00:52:31.450 --> 00:52:33.850
the great editor of the
Oxford English dictionary.

00:52:33.850 --> 00:52:37.020
In 1890, he figured out that
ketchup came from Chinese

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:40.310
because a missionary
in China mailed him

00:52:40.310 --> 00:52:43.017
an entry from his dictionary
because he had figured it out

00:52:43.017 --> 00:52:45.600
because he was talking to people
who were still using the word

00:52:45.600 --> 00:52:46.920
to mean the fish sauce.

00:52:46.920 --> 00:52:49.110
It's, by now, died
out, but in the 1880s

00:52:49.110 --> 00:52:52.060
it was still being used as a
word for a kind of fish sauce

00:52:52.060 --> 00:52:54.730
and somebody wrote it down.

00:52:54.730 --> 00:52:57.140
All etymology, you always
start with the Oxford English

00:52:57.140 --> 00:52:57.800
Dictionary.

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:00.427
But then it turns out that-- the
other thing the Oxford English

00:53:00.427 --> 00:53:02.760
Dictionary gives you is it
gives you the first citations

00:53:02.760 --> 00:53:05.190
of the word.

00:53:05.190 --> 00:53:08.890
So when I was teaching
at Boulder 20 years ago

00:53:08.890 --> 00:53:14.590
and I wanted to look at that
East India Company guide

00:53:14.590 --> 00:53:19.740
to Asia in 1690, I had
to request microfilm

00:53:19.740 --> 00:53:22.722
from some other university, I
had to wait till it arrived,

00:53:22.722 --> 00:53:24.930
then I had to go downstairs
into the library basement

00:53:24.930 --> 00:53:26.180
and read the microfilm.

00:53:26.180 --> 00:53:28.454
And now it's on Google
and you can search it.

00:53:28.454 --> 00:53:30.870
So if you look at the book and
you could just look for all

00:53:30.870 --> 00:53:32.286
uses of the word
ketchup in there.

00:53:32.286 --> 00:53:35.560
So the methods are much simpler.

00:53:35.560 --> 00:53:38.920
There's not that many
books written before 1800

00:53:38.920 --> 00:53:41.370
and they're all there so
you can search them all.

00:53:41.370 --> 00:53:43.020
So the research is
much more fun now

00:53:43.020 --> 00:53:45.000
because you can do
it in your bathrobe.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.102
It's very exciting.

00:53:47.102 --> 00:53:49.560
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
different languages might have

00:53:49.560 --> 00:53:53.960
different distributions of soft
versus sharp sounds and, if so,

00:53:53.960 --> 00:53:56.355
what that would say about the
origins of those languages?

00:53:56.355 --> 00:53:57.730
DAN JURAFSKY: Oh,
great question.

00:53:57.730 --> 00:54:01.720
So yes, there are certainly
different distributions

00:54:01.720 --> 00:54:05.010
of all sorts of things
across linguistically.

00:54:05.010 --> 00:54:10.880
I would say sound symbolism
is a cool phenomenon

00:54:10.880 --> 00:54:15.420
but is probably not a strong
factor in language change.

00:54:15.420 --> 00:54:19.070
So these two things, the
front versus back vowels

00:54:19.070 --> 00:54:21.859
and the soft versus the
sharp things, they do

00:54:21.859 --> 00:54:23.400
seem to affect
meaning and maybe they

00:54:23.400 --> 00:54:25.820
were important in how
meaning might have evolved

00:54:25.820 --> 00:54:29.750
for language, but there's
so many other factors that

00:54:29.750 --> 00:54:32.304
have much more magnitude
in how languages change

00:54:32.304 --> 00:54:33.345
and how languages evolve.

00:54:40.110 --> 00:54:42.320
Simplicity of
articulation in the mouth

00:54:42.320 --> 00:54:45.610
is a much stronger
drive for how words

00:54:45.610 --> 00:54:48.300
change their pronunciation,
say, than this kind

00:54:48.300 --> 00:54:50.139
of sound symbolic thing.

00:54:50.139 --> 00:54:51.930
That being said, there
are some differences

00:54:51.930 --> 00:54:53.638
but they seem to be
cultural differences.

00:54:53.638 --> 00:55:00.770
So, for example, this
finding that carbonated water

00:55:00.770 --> 00:55:04.430
is associated with sharp
sounds and flat water

00:55:04.430 --> 00:55:08.440
with round sounds was
not true in a study

00:55:08.440 --> 00:55:12.610
done in a tribe in Tanzania.

00:55:12.610 --> 00:55:15.080
So that may be true
only in Western society

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:18.800
where we perceive carbonated
water as sharp, somehow,

00:55:18.800 --> 00:55:21.200
or more acidic than flat
water but that's not

00:55:21.200 --> 00:55:23.030
a universal thing, necessarily.

00:55:23.030 --> 00:55:25.680
